    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that's a weird way to put it... but i guess i get the point. so if the interest is basically taking most of the money, how can i actually get ahead? like is there a specific way to make sure more of my money actually hits the principal instead of just covering the interest?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To get ahead, you need to be strategic about your payments. Think of it like a game of \"goblin-proofing\" your payments. Here's a trick: try to make extra payments whenever possible, especially when your income is high. This is like throwing a boulder into the goblin's path, blocking its ability to snatch as much interest as it can.\n\nYou can also consider making bi-weekly payments instead of monthly payments. This way, you'll be making 26 payments per year, rather than 12, which can help you chip away at the principal faster. Just be sure to check with your lender to see if this will affect your interest rate.\n\nAnother strategy is to pay more than the minimum payment when you can. This is like offering the goblin a \"gift\" – it might not take as much interest as it would if you only paid the minimum. Just be sure to check your budget and make sure you're not overextending yourself.\n\nLastly, consider consolidating your loans or refinancing to a lower interest rate. This is like trading in your old sword for a new one with a sharper blade – it can help you cut through the goblin's defenses and make your payments more manageable.\n\nRemember,",
      "source": "target",
